The paper deals with information processing and communication scenarios with privacy constraints. The problem formulation involves minimizing distortion subject to privacy constraints, which is a typical problem in information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the impact of privacy constraints on the strategic information transfer (SIT) model, which is a game-theoretic framework (cs.GT). The use of compression techniques for privacy preservation suggests a connection to multimedia (cs.MM) and signal processing (cs.SP). The paper also discusses the impact of communication channels on the equilibrium conditions, which is relevant to networking (cs.NI). Finally, the use of entropy-based privacy measures suggests a connection to cryptography (cs.CR) and machine learning (cs.LG).
